WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.600
Hi everyone, my name is Ben-Aaron Sebia, as you can see.

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:16.600
I'm here to talk about accelerating R adoption in GSK, but really what I want to talk to

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:21.600
you about is learning.

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:27.520
So learning, it's really, really, really hard.

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:29.280
Everyone knows that.

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:36.439
I think we within GSK, we're supposed to spend 20% of our time learning and developing.

00:00:36.439 --> 00:00:38.040
I don't know if we're able to do that.

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:39.040
It's difficult.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:40.639
It's really hard.

00:00:40.639 --> 00:00:46.959
And it's really hard to do learning and apply it to your job when you're working on books,

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:50.200
if you're working through articles, things like that.

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:51.840
So we're posed with this question.

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:57.720
How do organizations enable people to learn by doing, especially with these deadlines?

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:02.400
As you can probably see, I have TopGun here, and I promise I'm going to land this plane,

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:08.800
but TopGun is going to be throughout the presentation, and I'm going to relate it between the two.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:13.480
So you might be thinking, why is this bozo here able to talk about learning?

00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:17.000
So within GSK, I'm a director of data science.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
I lead our R enablement, which means I work a lot on our training, work a lot on enabling

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.720
people, building tools, things like that.

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:28.040
The most important thing is I'm really passionate about teaching and learning.

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:32.800
Right now, I'm reading a book about drawing, like learning how to draw, which is a very

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:38.360
humbling experience if you've ever tried to learn to draw as an adult.

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:41.080
Very humbling, but it's totally worthwhile.

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:43.599
All right, a little context.

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:45.800
What does a biostats organization do?

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:49.680
At the kind of core fundamentals, what we do is two things.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:55.440
One, we write statistical tests to determine if a drug or an asset is safe, and then the

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:57.839
second thing, is it effective?

00:01:57.839 --> 00:01:58.839
That's it.

00:01:58.839 --> 00:01:59.839
That is what we do.

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:04.279
We move things through the pipeline, and we write the tests to determine that.

00:02:04.279 --> 00:02:06.120
So huge change.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:12.240
In 2020, GSK Biostats, we decided to make R a primary language for statistical reporting.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:14.399
That is a huge deal for us.

00:02:14.399 --> 00:02:20.279
If you attend any sort of pharma conversation, presentation, this is a big deal for us as

00:02:20.279 --> 00:02:24.320
an industry as we move away from some other tools.

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:27.679
So we made this decision.

00:02:27.679 --> 00:02:30.360
So we made this decision.

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:33.080
We moved away from some proprietary tools.

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:34.399
So what did we do?

00:02:34.399 --> 00:02:35.960
We built a center of excellence.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:36.960
Everyone builds a center of excellence.

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:38.720
That's kind of the thing to do.

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:40.720
You got to do it.

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:46.639
So one of the things within that center of excellence was build a training program.

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:47.639
So that's what we did.

00:02:47.639 --> 00:02:48.919
We built one.

00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:53.460
And after a lot of failures, we finally figured out one that worked.

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:57.399
And today, we call it Accelerate R. Very clever name.

00:02:57.399 --> 00:02:59.600
You had to put R in it, right?

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:08.000
So when we started training people, when we started moving into R, what did we do?

00:03:08.039 --> 00:03:12.080
We started doing in-person training classes and virtual training classes.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:13.080
Why?

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:14.080
It's what we did last time.

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:15.220
It worked really well.

00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:17.279
It was perfect.

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:22.720
And as in Top Gun, they also had training in the classroom.

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:27.399
So we said, all right, let's just do what we did last time.

00:03:27.399 --> 00:03:30.440
Let's do in-person training, virtual classes.

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:32.240
We'll create some documentation.

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:34.960
We'll do some for our study teams.

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:40.199
We'll figure out what it is that they want, what it is that they need.

00:03:40.199 --> 00:03:41.199
And guess what?

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:43.479
They'll be able to do it, no problem.

00:03:43.479 --> 00:03:49.520
So that was the logic we applied.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:50.919
It did not work.

00:03:50.919 --> 00:03:54.639
We trained about 80% of GSK Biostats.

00:03:54.639 --> 00:03:58.160
Within GSK Biostats, we have about 900 people.

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:02.240
80% of those people went through that training.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:03.880
We just were not getting R adoption.

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:08.279
They weren't actually able to apply it to their clinical studies.

00:04:08.279 --> 00:04:11.160
So it wasn't working.

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:17.799
For Tom Cruise, it did not work either for the in-person training in the classroom.

00:04:17.799 --> 00:04:20.480
So what did we do?

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:24.880
We looked in the distance, like handsome Tom Cruise or Maverick.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.160
And we reflected, what was wrong?

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:30.839
Why was adoption so hard?

00:04:30.839 --> 00:04:32.859
Everyone went through all these trainings.

00:04:32.859 --> 00:04:35.179
Everyone was doing a lot of book clubs.

00:04:35.179 --> 00:04:39.019
Everyone was attending virtual meetups, things like that.

00:04:39.019 --> 00:04:44.420
Why were people not able to apply it to their clinical studies?

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:47.859
This was our big insight.

00:04:47.859 --> 00:04:51.619
Within clinical trials, you have huge lead times of projects.

00:04:51.619 --> 00:04:56.420
You will be on projects for years because of the nature of drug development.

00:04:56.420 --> 00:05:02.140
So one of the things that we saw frequently is someone would take an R training class.

00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:06.739
They would then wait 12 to 18 months before they applied it on a study.

00:05:06.739 --> 00:05:08.140
And guess what?

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:09.779
They totally forgot everything.

00:05:09.779 --> 00:05:12.320
I can't remember what I had for breakfast yesterday.

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:16.980
How are you going to remember what you learned in a training 12 months ago?

00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:21.700
So they forgot everything, and they were doing all the training on the fly.

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:22.980
It just wasn't sustainable.

00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:26.540
People were not willing to do it.

00:05:26.540 --> 00:05:31.899
The other thing with our R training, they were learning a huge amount of new things.

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:39.059
So when we say R training, we also mean GitHub, packages, a new way to think about data.

00:05:39.059 --> 00:05:43.079
Because how you interact with data within R is very different than how you might interact

00:05:43.079 --> 00:05:47.540
with it in other proprietary languages, different things like that.

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:50.820
It's incredibly overwhelming.

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:56.019
So it's not just, oh, I need to learn R. Let me call a library tidyverse.

00:05:56.019 --> 00:05:58.500
I actually need to figure out, how do I install R?

00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:02.779
What is the equivalent of a macro library to a package?

00:06:02.779 --> 00:06:03.779
Things like that.

00:06:03.779 --> 00:06:06.459
It's too much.

00:06:06.459 --> 00:06:11.119
We had this insight, so we proposed a change to our leadership team.

00:06:11.119 --> 00:06:13.420
No more classes, period.

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:14.420
No more training classes.

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:20.440
We're going to move all of our training into on-demand training and documentation.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:24.579
Why should I write a tidyverse training when someone else has done it a lot better than

00:06:24.579 --> 00:06:25.579
I ever could?

00:06:25.579 --> 00:06:26.579
I'm not going to do it.

00:06:26.579 --> 00:06:29.739
I'm just going to link out to it and use that.

00:06:29.739 --> 00:06:31.779
So what do we decide that we want to do?

00:06:31.779 --> 00:06:35.980
All the amount of time we would spend building out training courses, we're actually going

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:41.359
to make a small, agile team called Accelerate R, and that team is going to sit side by side

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:46.739
with a clinical study team and solve their problems with them and train with them at

00:06:46.739 --> 00:06:48.179
the same time.

00:06:48.179 --> 00:06:54.779
So instead of spending time actually building documentation, building virtual trainings,

00:06:54.779 --> 00:06:58.459
you're just going to actually spend the time with your study team.

00:06:58.459 --> 00:06:59.459
That's what we did.

00:06:59.459 --> 00:07:02.820
We're going to focus on support and mentoring.

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:06.619
So this is how we do it.

00:07:06.619 --> 00:07:11.179
It's really overwhelming, I fully admit it, but basically I'm going to take you through

00:07:11.179 --> 00:07:17.160
the process step by step on how actually Accelerate R works and works to train people and sit

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:19.119
with people.

00:07:19.119 --> 00:07:24.299
First off, once we've identified a clinical study that wants to work with the Accelerate

00:07:24.299 --> 00:07:29.299
R team, this small team of R experts, we say, great.

00:07:29.299 --> 00:07:32.660
Can you actually access R within our organization?

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:36.619
You do not, you cannot imagine the amount of times people will be like, I'm ready to

00:07:36.619 --> 00:07:39.940
use R, and you're like, great.

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:42.980
And then their first question is, how do I access it?

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:45.299
What system?

00:07:45.299 --> 00:07:49.380
First thing, you got to make sure that they actually have access to the system.

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:54.500
It's a silly thing, I realize, but it's a huge hurdle that a lot of people have in terms

00:07:54.500 --> 00:08:01.019
of actually beginning to use a new piece of technology within a large organization.

00:08:01.019 --> 00:08:05.179
After they get access, we go through an onboarding.

00:08:05.179 --> 00:08:09.739
So what the Accelerate R team will do is we do a week-long training up front about an

00:08:09.739 --> 00:08:13.359
hour a day, and we say, okay, what is it that you need to learn?

00:08:13.359 --> 00:08:14.859
What is your R maturity level?

00:08:14.859 --> 00:08:17.579
Are there specific problems that you're working on?

00:08:17.579 --> 00:08:20.579
Then we craft a training for them, specific packages.

00:08:20.579 --> 00:08:24.100
So maybe it's a team that's like, we know a ton about R already.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:25.220
I know how to use tidyverse.

00:08:25.220 --> 00:08:27.220
I know how to use ggplot.

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:29.140
I'm struggling with metadata.

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:31.619
We'll focus purely a week on metadata.

00:08:31.619 --> 00:08:36.020
It's probably not the most exciting week, but we'll do it for them.

00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:37.020
But that's what we do.

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:42.059
We do, first, an intro to these different packages based off the maturity level, and

00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:43.340
we say, great.

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:46.299
We did this week-long training with you.

00:08:46.299 --> 00:08:47.299
Let's deliver.

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:51.299
What we do then is we sit side-by-side with them for four two-week iterations.

00:08:51.299 --> 00:08:53.419
We work on the backlog with them.

00:08:53.419 --> 00:08:56.380
We build out their outputs with them.

00:08:56.380 --> 00:08:57.859
We do code reviews.

00:08:57.859 --> 00:08:59.900
We answer questions.

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:01.340
We have drop-in sessions.

00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:05.039
We are there to support them and help them with the creation of their outputs.

00:09:05.039 --> 00:09:10.539
So what we've done is take training, and we've actually just decided, all right, instead

00:09:10.539 --> 00:09:14.619
of doing sort of a virtual training teaching you how to use something, we're actually going

00:09:14.619 --> 00:09:20.140
to train you by working on an output that is going to go to a regulatory agency.

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:25.059
That is how we are doing our training now, and that is sort of our core tenet.

00:09:25.059 --> 00:09:27.460
No more training classes.

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:29.140
No more virtual trainings.

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:35.419
Teach as you need in order to create those outputs.

00:09:35.419 --> 00:09:37.539
Learn by doing.

00:09:37.539 --> 00:09:39.619
After that, we have a closeout.

00:09:39.619 --> 00:09:45.700
So the other big problem within Pharma is we have a 30-year history of using other tools

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:49.059
where we built out these huge code libraries that we can use.

00:09:49.059 --> 00:09:51.179
Within R, we don't have that.

00:09:51.179 --> 00:09:55.460
What we do is, sitting side-by-side, we learn what are their problems, how they go about

00:09:55.460 --> 00:09:56.460
solving it.

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:59.739
We then take that code, and we create a code library.

00:09:59.739 --> 00:10:03.539
That is how we are organically creating code libraries.

00:10:03.539 --> 00:10:07.539
So we have that kind of closeout and being able to learn, okay, what is it that they

00:10:07.539 --> 00:10:11.979
actually need to do, and then how is it that we can kind of learn by doing and take it

00:10:11.979 --> 00:10:16.340
and spread it across the organization.

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:17.979
We encountered some challenges again.

00:10:17.979 --> 00:10:22.859
So we were Maverick, and we looked in the distance, and we thought to ourselves, there

00:10:22.859 --> 00:10:23.859
are some issues.

00:10:23.859 --> 00:10:26.900
Let's think about this, and let's fix it.

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:31.099
Timing with Accelerate R is crucial.

00:10:31.099 --> 00:10:34.780
One of the big issues that we had is, from an Accelerate R team, is we were interacting

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:38.659
with study teams way too early.

00:10:38.659 --> 00:10:43.140
The way resourcing works within pharma is no one works on one study for the entire length

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:46.299
of that project.

00:10:46.299 --> 00:10:51.500
So when you actually jump in and help on a submission, it's really, really time-dependent,

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:53.659
and it's really important that you nail it.

00:10:53.659 --> 00:10:57.500
Because if you start to work with a submission team too far in advance, you might not have

00:10:57.500 --> 00:11:02.119
everyone there working on it, and as a result, your attendance and your ability to do training

00:11:02.159 --> 00:11:06.719
and interact with people, it's not going to be exactly what you would want.

00:11:06.719 --> 00:11:12.719
So you really need to think about that timing component.

00:11:12.719 --> 00:11:16.200
The other big thing, the learning curve.

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:21.000
I don't know who here has tried to teach anyone how to use Git or GitHub before.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.840
It is a journey.

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:29.159
So this is what we experience a lot, this huge, steep learning curve.

00:11:29.159 --> 00:11:32.039
People are like, ah, this is really hard.

00:11:32.039 --> 00:11:35.039
Then they get more and more and more confidence, and then as soon as they think that they've

00:11:35.039 --> 00:11:40.840
got it, something comes up, some internal process.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:47.239
For example, one of the issues I dealt with recently was with grobs within ggplot.

00:11:47.239 --> 00:11:48.479
I have no idea what I'm doing.

00:11:48.479 --> 00:11:51.599
I've used ggplot now for seven, eight years.

00:11:51.599 --> 00:11:52.880
I have no idea what's going on there.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:56.840
So I encounter this all the time, but this is a really important thing that you have

00:11:56.840 --> 00:12:00.880
to realize is going to happen when you're working with individuals and training them

00:12:00.880 --> 00:12:04.119
and teaching them.

00:12:04.119 --> 00:12:07.840
Some things did go well, all right?

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:12.919
One, we were able to expose lots of different people to lots of different tools.

00:12:12.919 --> 00:12:17.520
As I mentioned in the front, when you do R training, it's not just here, learn R, it's

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:22.200
here, learn R, here, learn GitHub, here, learn X, Y, Z, other tool.

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:25.880
Being able to expose people to all these different tools gives them a lot of confidence, and

00:12:25.880 --> 00:12:30.799
it helps us as an organization be able to say, great, we actually are progressing.

00:12:30.799 --> 00:12:32.599
We are moving.

00:12:32.599 --> 00:12:36.760
The second thing is we provided a route for the business to provide feedback.

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:40.359
As I mentioned, we have this center of excellence, and there's a lot of tools that that center

00:12:40.359 --> 00:12:43.880
of excellence wants to push out, but also get feedback.

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:47.559
This Accelerate R teams, because they sit side by side, they see what are the problems

00:12:47.559 --> 00:12:48.880
that study teams are having.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:53.479
It provides a route to provide that center of excellence a feedback on tools and also

00:12:53.679 --> 00:12:56.760
talk about what are the needs of the business.

00:12:56.760 --> 00:13:01.080
One of my colleagues, Becca, she's going to talk about Slushy, which was a direct output

00:13:01.080 --> 00:13:04.400
from that interaction with business teams.

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:07.059
The third thing is the farm reverse.

00:13:07.059 --> 00:13:09.280
It's an open source collaboration.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:12.919
Everyone's working on different packages from an industry point of view.

00:13:12.919 --> 00:13:17.039
It gives us an ability to say, yes, we can help contribute.

00:13:17.039 --> 00:13:21.119
We're training people on R. Then also, it allows us to point towards people who are

00:13:21.119 --> 00:13:26.640
super excited about the ecosystem as well as the programming language in the community.

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:34.159
It gives them a place to actually go and contribute and make a contribution to the community.

00:13:34.159 --> 00:13:38.200
The other thing is organizational resilience.

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:43.719
If anyone has ever been part of change management or change within a large organization, again,

00:13:43.719 --> 00:13:45.000
very, very hard.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.960
There's a lot of times where you're going to hit peaks and troughs, and you're going

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:51.159
to actually wonder, did I make the right decision?

00:13:51.159 --> 00:13:55.440
Being able to have people that are champions that are saying, yes, I learned a lot.

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:57.840
The support and mentoring has helped me change.

00:13:57.840 --> 00:14:02.719
It helps the organizational resilience get over that big cultural change that we as farm

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:06.960
art is encountering now, but other organizations encounter as well when they make these big

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:09.359
changes.

00:14:09.359 --> 00:14:16.760
So thinking about how do organizations enable people to learn?

00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:17.760
It's simple.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:18.760
Support them.

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:19.760
Mentor them.

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:26.799
Teach them on the job and actually focus on enabling them to deliver and supporting them

00:14:26.799 --> 00:14:29.640
to deliver using these new tools and technologies.

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:34.280
Make that change for them, and don't force them to try to learn how to do it on their

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:37.200
own through different trainings and things like that.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:41.280
Really just sit side by side and enable them through that support and mentoring.

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:43.200
So thanks, everyone.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:44.200
That's my talk.

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:50.200
Hopefully Tom Cruise was there along the way with us to be able to talk about training.

00:14:50.200 --> 00:14:57.000
Thank you so much, Ben.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:58.119
Appreciate it.

00:14:58.119 --> 00:15:04.039
Just as a reminder to those in this room, we have a way for you to be able to submit

00:15:04.039 --> 00:15:05.039
questions.

00:15:05.039 --> 00:15:16.080
It's under POSIT, P-O-S-I-T, forward slash Slido, S-L-I-D-O dash B, which is this room.

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:21.479
So I got a couple of questions here, but you're more than welcome to submit some.

00:15:21.479 --> 00:15:27.880
So one of the questions here, Ben, is why bundle Git with R learning instead of one

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:28.880
at a time?

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:35.599
Yeah, so the reason why we bundled it is because if you have ever tried to install an R package

00:15:35.599 --> 00:15:40.520
that is not on CRAN, you have to learn how to use dev tools and install through GitHub.

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:46.239
So we decided, you know what, let's just teach version control at the same time.

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:51.400
It might have been a bad mistake, but it is a mistake that we fully embrace and we continue

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:52.400
with.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:56.760
We also do a lot of version control within the organization for our study code.

00:15:56.760 --> 00:16:02.520
So just keep it all the same as part of the training.

00:16:02.520 --> 00:16:04.940
Great.

00:16:04.940 --> 00:16:09.599
When you are training a submission team, how do you find balance of teaching the core concepts

00:16:09.599 --> 00:16:14.119
without getting trapped into doing the analysis for them?

00:16:14.119 --> 00:16:16.239
It's a good question.

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:21.039
So when we interact with the team, we kind of have an up front conversation to say, here's

00:16:21.039 --> 00:16:22.039
what we're going to do.

00:16:22.039 --> 00:16:24.760
Here's what we're not going to do.

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:30.599
We sit by side, we help them solve their problems, but we are not part of the core submission

00:16:30.599 --> 00:16:31.599
team.

00:16:31.599 --> 00:16:36.119
So we just kind of scope that out and have very frank conversations.

00:16:36.119 --> 00:16:39.000
I live by this value called radical transparency.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.440
So with these subtle study teams, I am radically transparent in that I am not going to do their

00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:45.880
work, but I'm going to help them do their work.

00:16:45.880 --> 00:16:47.960
Thank you.

00:16:48.400 --> 00:16:49.400
Thank you.

00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:52.080
Also, what did primary in 2020 mean?

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:57.840
For example, was SAS, JMP, Solar, et cetera, used in the science doc?

00:16:57.840 --> 00:17:01.080
Did this impact code use to generate CSRs?

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:02.080
Good question.

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:07.880
So primary, what that means is we, what's the best way to put this?

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:14.520
So GSK, we have a philosophy of a multilingual world, which is right tool for the right person.

00:17:14.520 --> 00:17:20.280
As an example, if someone's been using SAS for 35 years, they might not want to use R.

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:22.119
And that's fine.

00:17:22.119 --> 00:17:28.719
So what that means in terms of a primary language is if you want to choose to use R as a language

00:17:28.719 --> 00:17:30.599
to do a submission, use it.

00:17:30.599 --> 00:17:32.079
I don't care.

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:38.619
But it's basically trying to make programming languages call it at the same level in terms

00:17:38.619 --> 00:17:43.839
of acceptance within an organization.

00:17:43.839 --> 00:17:48.640
The next question says, what is the most common hurdle you see as you train the new teams?

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:51.439
What is the most common hurdle?

00:17:51.439 --> 00:17:54.160
There are two things that I think are the most common hurdle.

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:59.920
One, how to think about data is dramatically different within R compared to SAS.

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:05.239
And I think that's really difficult for people to wrap their minds around.

00:18:05.359 --> 00:18:14.160
And then the other thing is there is a, people think of SAS macros and packages as one-to-one equivalents.

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:16.599
They are not one-to-one equivalents.

00:18:16.599 --> 00:18:24.359
So breaking people out of that kind of thought in terms of how do I actually find a function

00:18:24.359 --> 00:18:27.079
to use is really important.

00:18:27.079 --> 00:18:32.079
The number of times I've had to tell people don't write this custom function, it exists

00:18:32.079 --> 00:18:37.839
already in the Tidyverse or exists in this package, is too many to count at this point.

00:18:37.839 --> 00:18:42.199
I think we've got time for one last question here.

00:18:42.199 --> 00:18:48.160
How many people are on the Accelerator, Accelerate R team, and what is the typical ratio of Accelerator

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:52.719
R staff, members of research team being supported?

00:18:52.719 --> 00:18:53.760
So good question.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:19:01.560
So in terms of full time, we have three people that work on the team, but we have a secondment

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:02.560
model.

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:10.560
So oftentimes what will happen is after we interact with a clinical study team, one or

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:16.160
two individuals from that clinical study team will devote time to Accelerate R as we go

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:18.880
to the next study team.

00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:25.560
So it's a good way to not have to ask for headcount, but also at the same time provide

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:32.920
people the ability to train or work with other teams that they might not have the opportunity

00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:33.920
in the past.

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:34.920
Well, thank you again, Ben.

00:19:34.920 --> 00:19:35.920
Appreciate it.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:35.920


